value.value: A benign, usually encapsulated slow growing tumor of the peripheral nervous system composed of Schwann cells.  It recurs infrequently and only rare cases associated with malignant transformation have been reported.

A protective cover encircling a nerve, nerve fiber or axon.

value.value: A non-invasive adenocarcinoma arising from a tubulovillous adenoma.

A semi-synthetic analogue of Artemisinin - a sesquiterpene lactone extracted from the dry leaves of Artemisia Annua (sweet wormwood) used as anti-malaria agent. Limited data is available on Artemisinin antineoplastic activity.

A cell that belongs to the supporting tissue surrounding a nerve fiber bundle. It has thin long bipolar cytoplasmic processes, pinocytotic vesicles, fragments of external lamina and/or external lamina-like material, attachment plaques, and desmosome-like junctions.
Tissues that contain neurons and supporting cells that form the covers encircling nerves, nerve fibers, and axons.
A set of neural connections within the central nervous system, beginning with the retina and terminating in the occipital cortex, that provides the ability to process visual images.
Tissue located below the ependyma lining the ventricles of the brain and central canal of the spinal cord. It is a dense feltwork of glial processes and is believed to contain neural stem cells.
Space between the dura mater and the walls of the vertebral canal.
A non-invasive or invasive adenocarcinoma arising from a tubulovillous adenoma.
An area within the dura sheath but outside of the spinal cord.
A neuroepithelial cell that is situated just beneath the ependyma, which is the lining membrane of the ventricles of the brain and of the central canal of the spinal cord.
A microscopic finding indicating that the neoplastic cells exhibit an infiltrating growth in a tumor sample.
A microscopic finding indicating the formation of cystic structures in a tissue sample.
A morphological finding indicating the presence of newly formed blood vessels comprised of smooth muscle cells, pericytes and hyperplastic endothelial cells.

A type of carcinoma that comprises a minority of renal cell carcinomas.  It is characterized by loss of chromosomes 1 and Y.  Based on the cytoplasmic characteristics of the neoplastic cells, this type of carcinoma is classified as classic (typical), eosinophilic, or oncocytic.  It has a much better prognosis than other renal cell carcinomas.
A malignant epithelial neoplasm of the anterior pituitary gland in which the neoplastic cells stain positive with acidic dyes.
A morphologic finding indicating the presence of dense stromal fibrosis in a tissue sample.

Cardiovascular Alteration involves a change in the existing function of biologic molecules and complexes, or cellular, cell, or tissue components of the heart and vascular system by which blood is pumped and circulated through the body to provide tissues with oxygen and nutrients and to remove waste products.

Any therapeutic procedure that administers dihydrotestosterone, often transdermally, as androgen replacement therapy. Dihydrotestosterone therapy is intended to activate various biochemical processes that are dependent on the steroid.

Testosterone Secretion Induction consists of initiation of activities involved in release into the bloodstream by testicular interstitial (Leydig's) cells of the major androgenic steroid hormone (testosterone) produced in response to adenohypophyseal luteinizing hormone that regulates gonadotropic secretion; Wolffian duct differentiation into epididymis, vas deferens, and seminal vesicle; spermatogenesis after peripheral conversion to dihydrotestosterone by 5a-reductase; and skeletal muscle and bone tissue. Alteration of positive or negative feedback mechanisms can affect hormone release.

Estrogen Activity Inhibition involves interference with, such as receptor binding, or restraint of the biological function of biochemical substances (estrogens) secreted by the ovaries that have a specific regulatory effect on the activity of cells involved in development and maintenance of secondary female sex characteristics and control of the cyclical changes in the reproductive cycle, as well as pregnancy maintenance and an anabolic effect on protein metabolism and water retention.
A Respiratory Process involves the function of components of the respiratory tract involved in breathing, which include the nose, throat, larynx, trachea, bronchi, and lungs.

A Reproductive System Process involves a function of cellular, cell, or tissue components of the organ system involved in generation of offspring that includes the ovaries, fallopian tubes, uterus, cervix, and vagina in women or the prostate, testes, and penis in men.
